            <fr:title text="Dual space">Dual space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The dual space of a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^*]]></fr:tex>, is the vector space of all <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0061.xml" addr="FA-0061" title="Linear Functional">linear functionals</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> (i.e., linear maps from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> to the underlying field).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a normed vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, ||\cdot ||)]]></fr:tex>, the continuous dual space or topological dual space, often still denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X^*]]></fr:tex>, consists of all bounded (or continuous) linear functionals on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. A linear functional <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is bounded if there exists a constant <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M > 0]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f(x)| \leq  M ||x||]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The dual space plays a central role in functional analysis and helps establish important connections between a space and its "mirror image." The natural norm on the dual space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X^*]]></fr:tex> is the operator norm:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f|| = \sup \{|f(x)| : x \in  X, ||x|| \leq  1\}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Some important theorems related to dual spaces include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>The <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0065.xml" addr="FA-0065" title="Hahn-Banach theorem">Hahn-Banach theorem</fr:link>, which guarantees the existence of continuous linear functionals with specific properties</fr:li>
<fr:li>The <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0063.xml" addr="FA-0063" title="Banach-Alaoglu theorem">Banach-Alaoglu theorem</fr:link>, which states that the closed unit ball in the dual of a normed space is compact in the weak* topology</fr:li>
<fr:li>For <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert spaces</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, there is a canonical isomorphism between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> and its dual <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*]]></fr:tex> via the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0066.xml" addr="FA-0066" title="Riesz representation theorem">Riesz representation theorem</fr:link></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
